          "body": "One of Ezra 4's most striking features is what it does not say. From verse 8 through verse 23 — the entire Aramaic documentary section — God is not mentioned. The Persian bureaucrats do not invoke Him; the adversaries do not name Him; the king's reply is purely political. Yet the author's structure argues for God's invisible sovereignty throughout. The same Persian archive that Artaxerxes searches to condemn Jerusalem will be searched again in Ezra 5-6, and the searchers will find Cyrus's decree authorizing the very project Artaxerxes has stopped. The instrument of condemnation becomes the instrument of vindication. This is the pattern throughout Ezra-Nehemiah: God governs pagan kings without their awareness. Calvin's comment on this pattern is apt — God 'manages the counsels of princes and turns them wherever He pleases' (*Institutes* 1.16.6). The silence of the documentary section is not theological emptiness; it is a test of whether the reader will trust God's governance of events that appear purely secular."
