          "title": "The halt — 'until the second year of Darius'",
          "body": "Verse 24 is the chapter's most loaded sentence: 'Then work on the house of God in Jerusalem ceased, and it was stopped until the second year of the reign of Darius king of Persia.' The narrator does not soften the halt. The work stopped. The imperial decree was real; the force of arms was real; the cessation was real. Commentators who minimize verse 24 in favor of a triumphalist reading of the chapter misread the author's pastoral intention. The returnees faced a genuine defeat that lasted years. But the author does something subtle: he dates the halt. 'Until the second year of Darius' is not resignation — it is promise embedded in the grammar of apparent defeat. Any reader of Haggai already knows what happened in the second year of Darius (Haggai 1:1, 14-15): the Spirit of the LORD stirred Zerubbabel and Joshua, and the people came and worked on the house of the LORD. The halt has an expiration date set by God. This is the chapter's final word to the discouraged: the 'until' belongs to the LORD."
